## The 11 pillars

Each pillar is a distinct module of the app. Each has its own
tools, content, and Cy context. Pillars are vertical — a family
can dive deep into one while barely touching another. All 11
share the same data backbone so Cy can reason across them.

### Pillar 01: Who We Are — LIVE

**Purpose:** Identity and values. The family you're intentionally
becoming.

**Features:**
- Family name, tagline, and founding story
- Values document (5-10 core values, each with a definition)
- Culture canvas (rituals, rules, language the family uses)
- Household agreements (rules everyone signs off on)
- Mission statement (short, revisitable)

**Cy behavior:**
- Surfaces values when decisions touch them
- Asks quarterly: "Is this still who we are?"
- Notices drift (e.g., family named "rest" as a value but
  calendar is 95% full)

**Kid view:**
- Values shown visually (icons + words)
- "Who we are" story told age-appropriately
- Kids can add "what I'm proud of our family for"

### Pillar 02: The Partnership — LIVE

**Purpose:** The adult relationship at the center. Check-ins,
shared values, conflict repair, private space.

**Features:**
- Weekly partnership check-in (guided prompts, both responses
  saved)
- Shared values doc (partnership-specific)
- Couple calendar (date nights, trips, anniversaries)
- Sealed notes (each partner writes privately, revealed only
  when both opt in)
- Conflict repair framework (7-step guided process)
- Gratitude log (daily or weekly)

**Cy behavior:**
- Notices check-in cadence and surfaces when it's slipping
- Suggests conflict repair framework if "conflict" keyword
  appears in notes
- Never mediates live conflicts — always refers out

**Kid view:**
- Kids don't see the partnership pillar
- Only exception: anniversary countdowns for family context

**Privacy:** Partnership pillar is private from kids by default
and cannot be overridden.

### Pillar 03: Raising Your Kids — LIVE

**Purpose:** Each kid, named and known. Individual development,
not blob-level parenting.

**Features per kid:**
- Profile (name, DOB, photo, current age)
- School info (teacher, grade, address, schedule)
- Health basics (allergies, pediatrician, blood type)
- Developmental notes (what we're watching, milestones)
- Interests and passions (updated quarterly)
- Challenges (what they're working on, gently)
- Their love language
- Their parenting approach note (how we specifically parent
  THIS kid)
- Annual review (written once a year, archived forever)

**Cy behavior:**
- Surfaces individual kids when patterns emerge
- Reminds of upcoming milestones
- Suggests annual review when the kid's birthday approaches

**Kid view:**
- Each kid sees their own profile (age-appropriate fields only)
- Can add their own interests and "what I want mom/dad to know"

### Pillar 04: Time and Rhythms — LIVE

**Purpose:** Days, weeks, seasons. The heartbeat of family life.

**Features:**
- Shared family calendar (Google Calendar integration, both
  adults)
- Morning routine builder (per kid, per adult)
- Evening routine builder
- Family meeting protocol (this is a big one, see below)
- Season planner (quarterly cadence setter)
- Holiday and tradition tracker (annual recurring events)
- Weekly rhythm template

**The Family Meeting (the killer feature):**

Sunday evening, 30 minutes, both adults. Trellis walks you
through five structured steps:

1. **7-day audit** — Cy pulls both calendars. Walks through Mon
   through Sun. Asks 2-4 questions per day. You answer, Trellis
   captures.

2. **Pillar round** — Quick status across all 11 pillars. What's
   loud, what's quiet. Anything needing attention.

3. **Commit** — You pick 5 decisions max. Each becomes a task
   with owner, date, pillar tag.

4. **Capture** — Shopping list, meal plan, calendar adds, notes.
   All saved.

5. **Close** — One sentence from each adult. One prayer or
   intention. Done.

**Cy behavior:**
- Drives the Family Meeting flow (Cy is the facilitator)
- Notices when the meeting is overdue
- Flags patterns across weeks (e.g., "You've added 'date night'
  in commits 6 weeks in a row. Want to make it a recurring event
  instead?")

**Kid view:**
- Kids see their own morning/evening routines
- Kids see family calendar filtered to events relevant to them

### Pillar 05: Money and Stewardship — LIVE

**Purpose:** Budget, goals, generosity. How we steward what
we've been given.

**Features:**
- Monthly budget (categories, targets, actuals via CSV import)
- Savings goals (named, tracked, celebrated)
- Generosity log (tithing, donations, gifts)
- Financial calendar (bills, subscriptions, big payments)
- Debt tracker (payoff plan if applicable)
- Net worth snapshot (quarterly)
- Finance Friday ritual (weekly 15-min check-in guided by Cy)

**CSV import:** Users upload CSV from their bank or Monarch/YNAB
for now. Plaid integration deferred to 2027.

**Cy behavior:**
- Runs Finance Friday (Fridays, 4pm default, adjustable)
- Notices spending patterns against budget
- Surfaces savings goal milestones
- Never gives investment advice

**Kid view:**
- Kids see their SoboBucks balance (separate kid economy)
- Kids don't see family financials

### Pillar 06: Running the Home — JULY 2026 LAUNCH PRIORITY

**Purpose:** Meals, chores, inventory, flow. The physical house
working well.

**Features (v1, July 2026):**
- Weekly meal plan (7-day grid, breakfast/lunch/dinner)
- Grocery list (shared, add items tagged by meal)
- Chore rotation (daily, weekly, monthly rotations per person)
- Home inventory (cleaning supplies, pantry basics, reorder
  thresholds)
- Home maintenance calendar (HVAC filter, smoke detectors, etc.)

**Features deferred to v2:**
- Recipe library integration
- Voice/photo meal logging
- Smart fridge integration
- Auto-ordering via delivery services

**Cy behavior:**
- Generates weekly meal plan draft (reviewable by adults)
- Suggests grocery list from meal plan
- Reminds on maintenance cadence
- Tracks chore completion across kids

**Kid view:**
- Kids see their assigned chores with pictures
- Tap to mark complete
- Earn SoboBucks for completed chores

### Pillar 07: Health and Wellbeing — FALL 2026

**Purpose:** Body, mind, medical. Per person.

**Features:**
- Medical calendar (appointments, vaccinations, cleanings)
- Medication tracker (optional, per person)
- Family health history (hereditary conditions, allergies)
- Mental health resources (links out, not in-app therapy)
- Fitness/activity logging (light — not a fitness app)
- Sleep tracking (manual or device integration later)
- Wellbeing check-in (weekly per person, 3-question prompt)

**Cy behavior:**
- Surfaces upcoming appointments
- Notices missed medications (if tracked)
- Suggests wellbeing check-ins
- Escalates concerning patterns to "consider talking to a
  professional"

**Kid view:**
- Kids see their own appointments
- Can mark "how I'm feeling" with age-appropriate prompts

### Pillar 08: Your People — FALL 2026

**Purpose:** The community around you. Extended family, close
friends, godparents, mentors.

**Features:**
- People directory (names, how they relate, how to reach them)
- Birthday and anniversary calendar
- Prayer/intention list (who we're praying for or thinking of)
- Mentor relationships (both directions — who mentors us, who
  we mentor)
- Hospitality tracker (who we've had over, who's had us)
- Handwritten note log (who we should write, who wrote us)

**Cy behavior:**
- Reminds on birthdays (with a draft note suggestion)
- Surfaces people we haven't connected with in X months
- Suggests hospitality rhythm

**Kid view:**
- Kids see godparents, grandparents, close family friends
- "People who love you" visualization

### Pillar 09: Work and Purpose — FALL 2026

**Purpose:** Vocation for each adult. Career, calling, and the
rhythms that support them.

**Features (per adult):**
- Current role summary (company, role, start date)
- Career goals (short-term, long-term)
- Work calendar visibility to spouse (read-only)
- Side projects and passion work
- Reading/learning log
- Annual career review prompt

**Cy behavior:**
- Surfaces when one spouse's work is compressing on family time
- Annual career review reminder
- Notices learning/reading patterns

**Kid view:**
- Kids see "what mom/dad does" (age-appropriate summary)
- Optional: kids can contribute thoughts to parents' work
  patterns

### Pillar 10: Legacy — 2027

**Purpose:** What gets passed down.

**Features (scoped for 2027):**
- Annual letters to future generations
- Family recipe archive
- Tradition documentation (holidays, rituals, practices)
- Story archive (kids' stories, parents' stories, grandparents')
- Values across generations (what we're building on, what we're
  departing from)
- Financial legacy planning (wills, beneficiaries — light touch)

**Cy behavior (2027):**
- Annual letter prompts
- Story capture from conversations
- Tradition reminders

### Pillar 11: When It's Hard — 2027

**Purpose:** Crisis, conflict, grief, repair.

**This pillar is the most important and the most carefully
built.** Shipping it wrong would be worse than not shipping it.
That's why it's 2027.

**Features (scoped for 2027):**
- Crisis check-in mode (Cy goes quieter, meetings compress)
- Conflict resolution framework (7-step, already exists in
  partnership)
- Grief rhythms (how the family is actively grieving)
- Repair and reconciliation tracker
- Resource library (therapists, pastors, community)
- Emergency protocols (who to call, where things are)

**Cy behavior in crisis mode:**
- Reduces proactive messaging
- Only surfaces truly urgent items
- Redirects to human help early and often
- Never tries to be the counselor

